import DocLayout from "../../layouts/DocLayout.astro";
---

<DocLayout
    title="Architecture"
    description="Under the hood of Hearth: Effect.ts, Three.js, and FSM-driven logic."
    breadcrumb="Architecture"
    emoji="⚙️"
>
    <div class="intro">
        <p>
            Hearth is built on a modern, type-safe stack designed for
            performance, correctness, and longevity. We use Functional
            Programming (FP) principles to ensure the core logic is robust, and
            a component-based approach for UI flexibility.
        </p>
    </div>

    <h2>1. Technology Stack</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-8">
        <div class="glass-panel p-6 border border-white/10 rounded-xl">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-accent mb-2">Frontend Core</h3>
            <ul class="text-sm text-white/70 space-y-1">
                <li>
                    <strong>Astro</strong>: Static Site Generation (SSG) for
                    fast routing and zero-JS initial load.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>SolidJS</strong>: High-performance, fine-grained
                    reactivity for UI islands.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>TailwindCSS</strong>: Utility-first styling with
                    custom plugin system.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="glass-panel p-6 border border-white/10 rounded-xl">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-accent mb-2">Engine</h3>
            <ul class="text-sm text-white/70 space-y-1">
                <li>
                    <strong>Three.js</strong>: WebGL renderer for the 3D Music
                    Box scene.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>GSAP</strong>: Timeline-based animation
                    orchestration.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Effect.ts</strong>: Functional error handling,
                    dependency injection, and resource management.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>2. The FSM Config Parser</h2>
    <p>
        At the heart of Hearth is the <code>.conf</code> format — a simple, human-readable
        INI dialect that defines universal message parameters. We parse this using
        a strict <strong>Finite State Machine (FSM)</strong>.
    </p>
    <pre
        class="bg-black/40 p-4 rounded-lg text-xs font-mono text-white/80 overflow-x-auto border border-white/10">
// State Definitions
type FSMState = 'IDLE' | 'SECTION' | 'KV';

// Transitions
IDLE -> SECTION ("[header]")
SECTION -> KV (key=value)
KV -> KV (key=value)
KV -> SECTION ("[header]")
</pre>
    <p>
        This ensures that invalid configs fail gracefully with precise line
        numbers, and allows us to extend the schema without breaking legacy
        parsers.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Reactivity Model</h2>
    <p>
        Hearth uses SolidJS signals for state management. The <code
            >App.tsx</code
        > component orchestrates the entire lifecycle:
    </p>
    <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2 mt-4 text-white/70">
        <li>
            <strong>Loading Phase</strong>: Parallel fetch of config, audio, and
            texture assets.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Envelope Phase</strong>: Static HTML/CSS envelope
            interactive layer.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Scene Phase</strong>: 3D Canvas initialization. The <code
                >MusicBoxScene</code
            > class manages its own Three.js render loop but reacts to Solid props.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Finale Phase</strong>: Cleanup of WebGL context and
            transition to end card.
        </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>4. Decentralized Future</h2>
    <p>
        We are decoupling the data from the presentation logic. A Hearth message
        is just a JSON/Config object. This object can live on:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>LocalStorage (Drafts)</li>
        <li>Static Files (Current)</li>
        <li>IPFS / Arweave (Immutable)</li>
        <li>GunDB / P2P (Live Collaboration)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        The renderer (this app) is just a viewer for that data. This
        "Viewer/Data Separation" ensures that messages can outlive the platform
        itself.
    </p>
